   {:e #blake3 "b3b7df4cd6dc763a475d49ce8d5286a1318496cadf42fe9126cb4a06943459b4" :a :task/description :v "CONTEXT: daemon.rs:984-1029 is single-threaded synchronous accept. At 50 agents, requests serialize behind each other. A 3s status computation blocks all other agents for 3s. RATIONALE: Braid's grow-only set model means reads NEVER conflict with writes (set insertion commutes with set membership query). This is the fundamental property that enables unlimited read concurrency. Unlike a database, braid has NO read-write conflicts at the data level — only at the INDEX level (BTreeSet insertion), which is brief (microseconds). APPROACH: Replace the accept loop (~50 LOC change). Main thread: listener.accept() → spawn handler thread from pool. Handler thread: (1) Parse JSON-RPC request. (2) For read operations (status, query, guidance, task_ready): acquire RwLock::read() on Store (shared, unlimited concurrency). Execute tool handler. Release lock. Respond. (3) For write operations (observe, harvest, task_create, write_assert, task_go, task_close): submit WriteRequest to group commit channel (DS2). Await response on oneshot channel. Respond to CLI. Thread pool: bounded (8-16 threads), long-lived. Use std::thread::scope or a bounded threadpool crate. RWLOCK CHOICE: parking_lot::RwLock (fair, no writer starvation, reader-biased but with configurable fairness). Or std::sync::RwLock (simpler, sufficient for 50 agents). INVARIANT: INV-DAEMON-002 (store consistent with disk): refresh_if_needed() runs in the commit thread before each batch (not per-request — batch amortizes the check). ACCEPTANCE: (1) 10 concurrent status requests complete in < 2× single-request time (proving concurrency). (2) Write during concurrent reads: read results are consistent (either pre-write or post-write, never partial). (3) Thread pool does not grow beyond max_threads. (4) Connection timeout still works (30s). FILES: crates/braid/src/daemon.rs (~100 LOC refactor of serve_daemon). RISK: RwLock contention under write-heavy load (50 concurrent writes). Mitigated by DS2: writes go through commit channel, not direct lock acquisition. The RwLock exclusive hold is only during the commit thread's apply_datoms (~100μs)." :op :assert}
